<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-516-200  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 516 200.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 pSR19(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Customers take control of on-line services' future. (on-lineservices in the 1990s)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dunn, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>On-line services in the 1990s will be driven by such customerneeds as global information on companies, finance and politics;industry developments and trends; and full texts as well asabstracts and indexes.andP;  Customers are unhappy with disorganized,poorly integrated services with cluttered menus and want fixedcharges for unlimited usage and the right to share data.andP;  Threeforces shaping the on-line service market are the exponentialgrowth of information, accelerating business competition, and therestructuring of companies into less hierarchical forms.andP;  CUstomerrequirements are diverse, and vendors must adapt to the changingmodel.andP;  Dow Jones News Retrieval's Dowvision is an example offuture on-line directions; it delivers information to desktopsthrough corporate systems and offers a consistent interface andheterogeneous hardware architecture.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information servicesInformation Storage and RetrievalOn-LineFuture of ComputingForecastingData bases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>